        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Geo grid rank tracking</strong> checks your local search rankings from <strong>dozens of GPS coordinates across a map grid</strong>, showing exactly where you rank in the top 3 and where you fall out of the local pack. It turns "we rank #4" into a color-coded heatmap of proximity-driven ranking variance.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Typical grid</div>
            <div class="tms-value">25 to 100+ points</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Best cadence</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Monthly</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If you only check your local ranking from one location, you're seeing 1% of the picture. Proximity is one of Google's strongest local ranking signals — which means your ranking can go from #1 to #12 in the space of two city blocks.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is geo grid rank tracking?</h2>
        <p>Geo grid rank tracking is a local SEO measurement technique that queries Google from many GPS coordinates arranged in a grid around a business location. Each point runs the same keyword search and reports the rank the business holds at that spot. The output is a color-coded heatmap — green for top 3, yellow for 4-7, red for 8+.</p>
        <p>The grid usually contains 25 to 100 checkpoints spread across an area that matches the business's service radius. Because Google personalises local results by proximity, the same keyword can rank #1 near the storefront and disappear from the pack a mile out.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why a grid beats a single check</div>
          <p>Standard rank trackers use one location per keyword. That hides the reality of local: rankings often collapse rapidly outside the immediate area around the business pin. A grid quantifies that drop-off and shows you the real serviceable footprint.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why geo grid rank tracking matters</h2>
        <p>Once you see a heatmap, you can't unsee it. Three reasons every local operator runs one:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Proximity is a top-3 local ranking factor.</strong> Google's own documentation lists it alongside relevance and prominence. A grid quantifies exactly how far your ranking travels.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitor strongholds become visible.</strong> The red patches show where a competitor's pin dominates. That is where you either build hyperlocal content or accept the boundary.</li>
          <li><strong>Near-miss opportunities surface.</strong> Positions 4-7 are the fastest wins — one strong review week or a targeted neighbourhood page often lifts them into the pack.</li>
          <li><strong>You can prove growth over time.</strong> Watching the green area expand month over month is one of the few local SEO metrics that maps cleanly to phone calls and direction requests.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How geo grid rank tracking actually works</h2>
        <p>Every geo grid tool follows the same four-step loop.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># 1. Define the grid</span><br>
          center: <span class="uf-new">business pin (lat, lng)</span><br>
          size: <span class="uf-status">7 x 7</span> (= 49 points)<br>
          spacing: 0.5 miles between points<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># 2. Query each point</span><br>
          for point in grid:<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;GET google.com/search?q=<span class="uf-old">"emergency dentist"</span>&amp;near=point<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;record: rank of business + top competitors<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># 3. Render the heatmap</span><br>
          <span class="uf-status">green</span> = top 3 &nbsp;·&nbsp; <span class="uf-label">yellow</span> = 4 to 7 &nbsp;·&nbsp; <span class="uf-old">red</span> = 8+<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># 4. Compare across months</span><br>
          diff current vs previous → track green expansion
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">Grid sizes and when to use them</h2>

