        <h2 id="examples">Real geo grid tracking examples</h2>
        <p>Two anonymised results from client audits — both used the same 7x7 grid month over month.</p>

        <h3>1. Dental practice — west-side blind spot</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Baseline (Jan)</span><br>
          east grid: <span class="uf-status">avg rank 2.4</span> (green)<br>
          west grid: <span class="uf-old">avg rank 7.1</span> (red)<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># After 3 months of west-side neighbourhood pages</span><br>
          west grid: <span class="uf-status">avg rank 3.8</span> (green/yellow)
        </div>
        <p>The fix was two hyperlocal landing pages plus five review requests from patients whose home addresses fell in the red zone.</p>

        <h3>2. HVAC company — ranking radius expansion</h3>
        <p>Baseline: 12 of 49 grid points ranked in the top 3. After six months of consistent GBP posts, service-area landing pages, and citation cleanup, that grew to 31 of 49 — a 2.6x expansion of the green area with no change in overall keyword ranking.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Geo grid vs standard rank tracking</h2>
        <p>Both check where you rank. The difference is scope and what you can do with the answer.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use geo grid when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You have a physical location or service area</li>
              <li>You want to see proximity drop-off</li>
              <li>You need to prove ranking expansion visually</li>
              <li>You're competing with a nearby local player</li>
              <li>You're planning neighbourhood-level content</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use standard rank tracking when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You rank nationally, not locally</li>
              <li>The keyword has no local intent</li>
              <li>You want long-term trend graphs per keyword</li>
              <li>You need SERP feature tracking, not proximity</li>
              <li>You're an e-commerce or SaaS brand</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for geo grid rank tracking</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Match grid size to service radius.</strong> A downtown cafe needs a tight 3x3; a plumbing company covering a metro needs a 9x9 or larger.</li>
          <li><strong>Track 3-5 money keywords, not 50.</strong> Grids are expensive to run. Focus on the terms that convert.</li>
          <li><strong>Screenshot the heatmap every month.</strong> Progress storytelling beats raw numbers when reporting to owners.</li>
          <li><strong>Watch the yellow zone.</strong> Positions 4-7 are the fastest lifts — one review week or one landing page often flips them green.</li>
          <li><strong>Overlay competitor grids.</strong> Where they own green, ask why: is it a keyword in their business name, more reviews, or a service page?</li>
          <li><strong>Pair with GBP Insights.</strong> A green grid that produces zero calls means the listing itself needs work, not the rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>Run before and after every intervention.</strong> Rewrote the GBP description? New citations? Prove the delta with a fresh grid.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — treating averages as truth</div>
          <p>Reports that show "average rank across the grid" hide the reality. Two grids with the same average can look totally different — one with a hot centre and dead edges, one with even mediocre coverage. Always look at the actual heatmap, not the number.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common geo grid tracking mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Grid too small</strong> — a 3x3 on a service area business misses 80% of the pull area.</li>
          <li><strong>Grid too large</strong> — a 15x15 on a coffee shop wastes credits on points nobody would drive from.</li>
          <li><strong>Running once, then never again</strong> — the value is the delta over months, not any single snapshot.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the top-3 competitor changes</strong> — track who else appears in each grid cell, not only your rank.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimising the whole grid at once</strong> — pick the yellow zones near where you already win. Compounding beats scattering.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps you run geo grid tracking</h2>
